    "created_at": "2019-03-05T14:27:29Z",
    "updated_at": "2019-03-05T14:27:29Z",
    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "I think an `axis` argument to `set_index` would be a good idea since for the `df.columns = ` method you have to create a new variable. A common case is where you want to rename the columns of a data frame before joining it to another one:\r\n\r\n```\r\ndf.join(df2.set_index(['X', 'Y', 'Z'], axis=1))\r\n```\r\n\r\nThis is much more elegant than\r\n\r\n```\r\ndf3 = df2.copy()\r\ndf3.columns = ['X', 'Y', 'Z']\r\ndf.join(df3)\r\n```\r\n\r\nand still better than\r\n\r\n```\r\ndf.join(df2.rename(columns={'A': 'X', 'B': 'Y', 'C': 'Z'}))\r\n```"
  }
